    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Hi @rogerroelofs, thanks for reporting this issue and for the associated PR! Here are my comments:\n\n> This change will autoHide the toggle if changing it's state would result in 0 hits.\n\nThis would be in-line with what is done today for other widgets indeed. But we could maybe also do something a bit different: what if as soon as we know toggling would result in no hits we show the toggle as disabled? As for the default rendering it would mean adding `disabled` to the toggle checkbox element.\n\nThen we would be able to still allow the user to untoggle if the current state is 0 hits and untoggling would mean showing some hits.\n\nWhat do you think?\n\n> In the case where the off state doesn't have a value (i.e. means don't use the attribute in the search) the count should be the number of hits for 'don't use' rather than the number of hits for 'false'\n\nThat's right and this we can change it.\n\nI am blow away by the fact that you understood so much from our codebase and were able to hack in the toggle code which is not that easy to understand (read: complex, not smart :p).\n\nIf you are down to continue this PR based on my first comment then go for it, add tests if you feel like it otherwise we will do it.\n\nThanks a lot\n",
